The objective doesn't explicitly mention clicking on any links to go to a new page to search for hotels in New York, but we can infer that we would need to search for hotels by location. Since our current page is https://www.booking.com/ and there's a "Stays" link on the navigation bar, we could possibly click on "Stays" or another more suitable link and then search for "New York", however there is a option visible in the tree (Navigation: What are you looking for?) that seems to have options for different types of bookings, but does not have an input field for location. Unfortunately, "Stays" link is visible but we cannot search from the current page directly based on provided Accessibility Tree. We can click on "Stays" to try find more suitable interface.

Let's think step-by-step. Currently, I'm on the Google Street View page of The Museum of American Heritage. My task is to find the most wheelchair-accessible museum near me with parking and entrance ramps visible in Google Street View. Since I'm already in Street View, I should be able to see if there are parking and entrance ramps visible. From the current accessibility tree, it seems that I can press the next button to explore more of the museum's surroundings.

However, I would like to zoom out and get a better view of the whole area. The zoom in function was performed in a previous action, but I can do the opposite by using the Zoom out function which has id [660] in the previous actions but not in the current tree but looking at [410] where [410] is Zoom in. Since the 'Zoom in' and 'Zoom out' button could be the opposite or similar to each other, it could be [410] also. Alternatively, I will check the list items and other buttons. I can see another button [127] application 'Street View', but it is a Canvas so there is nothing to click or more useful buttons. Now I can see that there are some tablist and listitem buttons but they don't have 'Zoom out' so they aren't useful here. Why not try some alternative that can help find the zoom out? 

As per this analysis, [410] might do what we are looking for.

To gather more information, I want to view the first photo. This photo is listed as a link in the accessibility tree.
